a. Purpose of Key Directories

/bin (Binaries)
Contains essential command-line programs needed for basic system operation.
Examples: ls, cp, mv, cat

/etc (Configuration Files)
Stores system-wide configuration files and settings.
Examples: passwd, hosts, ssh/sshd_config

/home (User Home Directories)
Contains personal directories for each user.
Examples: /home/user/Documents, /home/user/Downloads

/var (Variable Data)
Holds data that changes frequently during system operation.
Examples: log/, spool/, cache/

/usr (User Programs & Data)
Stores installed applications, libraries, and documentation.
Examples: /usr/bin, /usr/lib, /usr/share

/tmp (Temporary Files)
Stores temporary files created by applications and users.
Examples: session files, temporary downloads (often cleared on reboot)

b. Summary

Each directory in Linux has a specific role that helps organize the system efficiently, improve security, and simplify management.
